## 5. RESOLUTION-INDEPENDENCE ‚Äî confirmed

Correction **must** be:

\[
\Delta z = \frac{1.0}{\text{width}}, \quad \Delta w = -\frac{1.0}{\text{height}}
\]

using the **same** `width`/`height` already in `setViewport`. No literals like `512`, `1024`, or `0.5f` as pixel offsets in clip space.

‚ÄúSeam persists at higher resolution‚Äù is consistent with a **fixed ¬Ω-px screen error**, which is exactly **`1/w`** in NDC ‚Äî it doesn‚Äôt vanish when `w` grows.

---

## 6. REGRESSION RISK ‚Äî what a central c9 edit actually does

### Expected behavior (if theory is right)

**Every** XYZRHW 2D draw (splash, HUD, fonts, radial menu, char-select 2D) moves ‚âà**¬Ω px toward D3D9 parity**. That is the intended global correction, not an accidental side effect.

### Real failure modes to watch

| Risk | Cause | What to look for |
|------|-------|------------------|
| **Double correction** | Some other D3D11 path already applies ¬Ω-px fudge | Global ‚âà1 px shift; text blur; UI off screen edges |
| **Wrong sign** | `z -= 1/w` or `w += 1/h` | Systematic shift opposite D3D9; seam may worsen |
| **Wrong magnitude** | `0.5/w` | Seam attenuated but not gone; UI still soft |
| **Viewport-origin interaction** | Accidentally baking correction into `xOffset`/`yOffset` instead of base `.z`/`.w` | Sub-viewport UI (scissor regions) misaligned while fullscreen looks fine |
| **3D pollution** | c9 shared with non-2D shaders | Unlikely given VS guard + `transform2d()` scope ‚Äî but verify no 3D VS reads c9 |

### No-regression sweep (D3D11 vs D3D9 reference)

- **Load screens:** center seam gone on multiple splashes and resolutions.
- **HUD / chat / tooltips:** text crispness (no extra blur), no systematic 1 px drift vs D3D9 captures.
- **Screen edges:** full-bleed UI still flush to borders.
- **Radial menu / char-select:** circular/radial elements still centered; no oval distortion (scale terms unchanged).
- **Scissored subregions:** inventory panes, nested viewports ‚Äî alignment unchanged relative to D3D9.

If splash fixes but HUD regresses vs D3D9, suspect **sign/magnitude error or double correction**, not ‚Äúc9 was the wrong layer.‚Äù

